SNR2a;max¬Ωe¬ä Ô¨É 4√∞N=M√û:

√∞13√û

We will use this slightly less precise approximation below. The fact that the squared SNR in equation (13) is propor-
tional to the third power of the spatial resolution √År  (V/M)1/3, where V  |√Åq|√Ä1 is the reconstructed volume in the object space, rather than to the fourth power, as shown previously (Howells et al., 2009), is the consequence of our (unrealistic) assumption that the voxel volume, |√Åqm|, is uniform throughout the diffraction space. This would be the case if the diffraction intensity data were collected on a regular Cartesian grid qmmm&  √∞mh; mh; m&h√û in the diffraction space, where m, m and m& are integers, each spanning the set f0; 1; 2; . . . ; L √Ä 1g, L3 = M. However, this is difÔ¨Åcult to achieve in a real CDI experiment. When the diffraction data are collected on a regular cylindrical grid, which is the case when the sample is rotated around a Ô¨Åxed axis, similar to conventional parallel-beam computed tomography (CT), the average squared SNR is known to be proportional to the fourth power of the spatial resolution (Natterer, 1986), and is given by

SNR2a;max¬Ωe¬ä Ô¨É 4N=M4=3;

√∞14√û

where  is a dimensionless constant of the order of unity, which depends on the sampling and interpolation schemes, but not on the collected diffraction intensities (numbers of photons) (Gureyev et al., 2016). Compared with equation (13), here the additional power of √År in the expression √Å4r = (V/M)4/3, appears as a consequence of the ‚Äòramp‚Äô Ô¨Åltering, arising from the multiplication of the collected diffraction intensity data nR;h;T √∞qm√û by coefÔ¨Åcients proportional to s = (2 + &2)1/2 in the reconstruction process (Gureyev et al., 2016). In turn, the presence of the ramp Ô¨Ålter in the reconstruction process is a direct consequence of the linear non-uniformity of the elemental voxel volume as a function of the radial coordinate in the cylindrical case. Indeed, the elemental volume in cylindrical coordinates is equal to |dq| = s ds dd, assuming that the sample is rotated around the y axis (which is parallel to the  axis) during the scan (Fig. 1). This means that the higher order diffraction orders are actually being measured with lower precision (higher noise) when the detector pixels are uniform in size, because the sampling density linearly decreases as a function of the radial coordinate, s. In terms of the singular value decomposition (SVD) of the relevant reconstruction operator (which implements the inverse parallel-beam X-ray transform in three dimensions), the same effect leads to the singular values being equal to lmm ¬º √∞l √æ 1√û1=2=√∞4√û, s = lh, which increase in proportion to the square root of the radial order l of the corresponding basis functions (Natterer, 1986). Such behaviour of the SVD usually results in the ampliÔ¨Åcation of noise relative to the useful signal in the collected intensity data, and hence in lower SNR in the reconstructed sample, as in equation (14), compared with

equation (13). This happens because the magnitude of a typical diffraction signal decreases as a function of |q|, and hence the relative amount of shot noise increases with |q|. Therefore, when the reconstruction ampliÔ¨Åes high-order diffraction components, relative to the low-order ones, it effectively ampliÔ¨Åes the noise with respect to the signal. This effect is demonstrated explicitly below.
Considering the case where the imaged sample is rotated in an arbitrary continuous way in three-dimensions, we note Ô¨Årst that in order to provide a unique reconstruction of the sample, the set of all sample orientations used during the scan must satisfy the Orlov condition (Natterer, 1986; Orlov, 1975; Defrise et al., 1993). It is easier to describe this condition by specifying that the sample is stationary, while the source and the detector are synchronously rotated around the sample (as e.g. in medical CT), instead of the equivalent real situation where the source and the detector are Ô¨Åxed and the sample is rotated (as in synchrotron-based CDI). Let S2 be a Ô¨Åxed sphere enclosing the sample, and p denote a vector extending from the centre of the sphere to its surface and orthogonal to the detector plane. In the continuous case, the Orlov condition states that the line √à, drawn on S2 by the vector p while the detector is rotated during the scan, must intersect all great (equatorial) circles on S2 (Fig. 1). For example, when the detector is rotated by 180 around the y () axis, as in conventional parallel-beam CT, the line √à simply coincides with an equatorial semicircle. The Orlov condition is obviously satisÔ¨Åed in this case, because all equatorial circles on a sphere intersect any Ô¨Åxed equatorial semicircle. In general, when the detector is rotated arbitrarily around S2, the line √à does not lie in a single two-dimensional plane. However, it is still possible to introduce curved coordinates in a three-dimensional solid sphere enclosed by S2, where the ‚Äòrotation angle‚Äô parameter ‚Äô parameterizes the line √à on the surface, while two other coordinates (s, ) determine a position within the plane √Ö() through the centre of the sphere with the normal vector pointing to √à() (Fig. 1). If Orlov‚Äôs condition is satisÔ¨Åed, the plane, √Ö(), sweeps the whole solid sphere, while the normal vector travels along the line √à. If s is parallel to the vector dp() tangential to line √à at point , and  is perpendicular to s within the two-dimensional plane √Ö(), then the elemental three-dimensional volume in these coordinates will be the same as in the cylindrical case, i.e. |dq| = s dsd d. Therefore, in the case of optimal Shannon sampling, the SNR here will be the same as in the cylindrical case above, i.e. as in equation (14). Finally, if the rotational positions during the ‚Äòscan‚Äô are discrete (and can be random in the XFEL-type CDI), a sufÔ¨Åcient condition for Shannon sampling can be formulated in the following way. Mapping all rotational positions √àm of the sample as points on S2, it should be possible to draw a continuous line √à through all or a subset of the points √àm in such a way that: (i) the line √à satisÔ¨Åes the Orlov condition; (ii) the distance between points √àm along the line √à does not exceed R√Å = 2R/L, where L2 is the total number of pixels in the detector (assuming that detector pixels are square and do not have gaps between them). The condition √Å = 2/L is further discussed below.

IUCrJ (2018). 5, 716‚Äì726

Timur E. Gureyev et al.  Signal-to-noise, spatial resolution and information capacity 721

research papers

One might think that the difference between equations (13)

and (14) is artiÔ¨Åcial, as any diffraction data collected on a

cylindrical, spherical or other sufÔ¨Åciently dense and regular

grid can be readily interpolated onto a suitable Cartesian grid,

which would then lead to equation (13), rather than equation

(14). However, it is known that the corresponding interpola-

tion tends to amplify the noise in the measured data (Natterer,

1986), thus leading to a higher power of M in the denominator

of equation (14). This is also true for random orientations of

the sample, where the corresponding normal vectors p uniformly sample the whole sphere S2. According to the Orlov

condition, such sampling may be overdetermined (e.g. a

sufÔ¨Åciently dense set of points on a single equatorial semicircle

already provides optimal sampling). Therefore, the behaviour

of the SNR will be expected to depend on the interpolation

scheme employed for remapping the sampling points from the

original scan grid points to a regular grid used in the recon-

struction. Some methods may actually skip this remapping

step and utilize the original grid points directly (Elser, 2009),

but the stability of the method, and hence the SNR in the

reconstructed electron-density distribution, will still inevitably

depend on the geometry of the sampling grid, as demonstrated

on a fundamental level by the behaviour of the singular values

of the X-ray transform (Natterer, 1986). An estimate of the

number of CDI projections required to provide Shannon‚Äôs

sampling, in the case of random orientations of the sample

uniformly distributed on a sphere, was given in Ekeberg et al.

(2015). This number is consistent with the Orlov condition and

the optimal angular sampling requirement in CT (Natterer,

1986), as discussed below.

